      "id": "saints-their-honorary-miracles-al-karamat",
      "number": 4,
      "title": "Saints & Their Honorary Miracles (al-Karāmāt)",
      "description": "It is a Creedal Obligation to have generic belief in the Honorary or Lesser Miracles (al-Karāmāt) of God’s Saints. It is not, however, obligatory to believe in reports about individual cases of those Saintly Miracles unless they are…",
      "sections": [
        {
          "id": "saints-their-honorary-miracles-al-karamat",
          "title": "Saints & Their Honorary Miracles (al-Karāmāt)",
          "level": 3,
          "parentId": null,
          "content": "<p>It is a Creedal Obligation to have generic belief in the Honorary or Lesser Miracles (<em>al-Karāmāt</em>) of God’s Saints. It is not, however, obligatory to believe in reports about individual cases of those Saintly Miracles unless they are definitively established by authentic transmissions. Muslim Scholars of Divinity define the Lesser Miracle (<em>al-Karāma</em>) of the non-Prophetic Saint as: “A matter that appears at the hands of one of God’s Saints which breaks the norms of Customary Reality and is linked with the Direct Knowledge [of God] and Obedience [of Him], while being free of [any] claim to Prophecy” (<em>Amr khāriq li-al-‘Āda maqrūn bi-al-Ma‘rifa wa al-Ṭā‘a khāl ‘an da‘wat-al-Nubūwa</em>). The greatest of all Honorary Miracles is inward and outward Rectitude (<em>akbar Karāma: al-Istiqāma</em>). Among the manifest <em>Karāmāt</em> of God’s Saints are His Closeness to them, together with the great Knowledge and Protection He grants them. Al-Imām al-Bukhārī and other Scholars of <em>Ḥadīth</em> transmit authentically from the Prophet that he said in a well-known Divine <em>Ḥadīth</em> (<em>Ḥadīth Qudsī</em>):</p><p>Whoever transgresses against one of My Saints, I have declared war against him. My Servant does not draw near to Me by anything more beloved to Me than what I have made obligatory upon him. He does not continue to draw closer to Me by voluntary deeds of Good until I love him. When I love him, I become his hearing with which he hears, his sight with which he sees, his hand with which he smites, and his foot with which he walks. Truly, if he asks [anything] of Me, I will surely give it to him, and if he takes refuge in Me I will surely grant it to him. There is nothing that I am about to do regarding which I am more hesitant than [taking] the Believer’s Soul. He dislikes death, and I dislike making him anything but happy. </p><p>     An example of an authentic Honorary Miracle of the<em> Awliyā’</em> is the account of the ancient Christian youths—probably Greek speaking—who lived during the time of the Great Persecutions. They sincerely followed the original teachings of Jesus Christ, and openly refused to worship the Roman Emperor of their time, boldly declaring God’s Oneness before him and their people. Forced to flee persecution, they escaped together with their dog to a hidden mountain cave. There, God made them fall into a deep slumber at the mouth of the cave and kept them there unchanged and protected from harm for three hundred years by the solar calendar and three hundred and nine by the lunar. When God raised them from their sleep, they discovered by chance that—during the interval of their centuries of slumber—their people had become Christian. Their reappearance into society thus became a decisive Sign of the Truth of the Resurrection, a matter over which disagreement and doubt had arisen among the Christians (See Qur’ān, 18:9-26).</p><p>     The Honorary Miracles of the Saints may be called “lesser Miracles,” for they share in the nature and general status of the Prophetic Miracles (<em>al-Mu‘jizāt</em>) as clear indications that a Saint (<em>Walī</em>) is truly walking in the footsteps of the Prophets. Accordingly, each Honorary Miracle of a <em>Walī</em> of God constitutes a later Miracle for the Prophet whom he or she follows. Thus, just as the Prophet-Messenger Jesus Christ brought the dead to life by Miracle (<em>Mu‘jiza</em>), several great Muslim Saints in history have also brought the dead to life as Honorary Miracles (<em>Karāmāt</em>). The <em>Walī</em> must, however, never seek to be given Honorary Miracles nor take pride in them, display them ostentatiously, or become deluded when they occur. It is said that the true <em>Walī</em> of God hides his or her Honorary Miracles away as “shames” and buries them deep in the seventh Earth. Indeed, by contrast, one of the distinguishing Signs of the False Shaykh and Hypocritical Saint is that they seek to attain or simulate Honorary Miracles and use them to advance their interests and control people. As we will see in Volume Seventeen, non-Miraculous Diabolical violations of Customary norms also exist, and the Believer must learn how to distinguish carefully between the true<em> Karāmāt</em> of God’s Saints and Satanic inversions of them. For untrained, inexperienced, and naïve Believers often confuse “the Saints of Satan” with the true Saints of God <a href=\"/v/17/saints-their-honorary-miracles-al-karamat/web-extension\" class=\"web-extension-chip\" data-web-extension-link=\"true\" aria-label=\"Open web extension 4\">Web-Extension 4</a>.</p><p>Book Two: Sufism, Spirituality, &amp; Authentic Shaykhs</p>",
          "pageReference": 4,
          "footnotes": []
        }
      ]
